and he was my teacher.

01:09:38.420 --> 01:09:41.200
I still remember these moments
from classroom.

01:09:41.200 --> 01:09:47.010
And he was teaching us
about these subjects.

01:09:47.010 --> 01:09:50.152
He was thinking about examples
of investments --

01:09:50.152 --> 01:09:51.230
and he said, you know what?

01:09:51.230 --> 01:09:56.960
One of the best investments I
can think of is a honeymoon.

01:09:56.960 --> 01:09:59.760
When you get married, you
go on a vacation.

01:09:59.760 --> 01:10:02.150
Now, why are you doing that?

01:10:02.150 --> 01:10:05.100
Is it for fun?

01:10:05.100 --> 01:10:05.910
Probably not.

01:10:05.910 --> 01:10:08.120
In fact, I have a suspicion
that most

01:10:08.120 --> 01:10:10.410
honeymoons are not fun.

01:10:14.170 --> 01:10:17.900
I think it's just people are
too uptight and tense.

01:10:17.900 --> 01:10:19.340
What have we just done?

01:10:19.340 --> 01:10:22.300
And I bet that's right.

01:10:22.300 --> 01:10:24.530
So, why do you do it?

01:10:24.530 --> 01:10:27.020
Well, you do it as an
investment, right?

01:10:27.020 --> 01:10:29.205
You want this photograph
album.

01:10:29.205 --> 01:10:30.390
You want the memories.

01:10:30.390 --> 01:10:32.570
You're kind of bonding.

01:10:32.570 --> 01:10:34.950
I think he's absolutely right.

01:10:34.950 --> 01:10:37.330
You should go on a honeymoon.

01:10:37.330 --> 01:10:38.460
So, I did another search.

01:10:38.460 --> 01:10:41.530
I searched on honeymoon loans.

01:10:41.530 --> 01:10:43.830
And I got 1.7 million hits.

01:10:43.830 --> 01:10:45.630
It beat vacation loans.

01:10:45.630 --> 01:10:48.600
So, there are many lenders
ready to lend.

01:10:48.600 --> 01:10:50.170
And you should do it.

01:10:50.170 --> 01:10:55.540
If you're just getting married
and you don't have any money,

01:10:55.540 --> 01:11:03.170
go to the usurious guy and ask
for the honeymoon loan.

01:11:03.170 --> 01:11:05.040
So, I'm not sure whether
it's bad.

01:11:05.040 --> 01:11:06.550
This is a question.

01:11:06.550 --> 01:11:08.050
I think that there
are abusers.

01:11:08.050 --> 01:11:10.970
And I wanted to just close
with Elizabeth Warren.

01:11:13.590 --> 01:11:16.420
I first met her just
a few years ago.

01:11:16.420 --> 01:11:17.770
Well, actually, I remember
her book.

01:11:17.770 --> 01:11:20.750
She wrote some important
books.

01:11:20.750 --> 01:11:24.670
She's a Harvard law professor
who wrote books.

01:11:24.670 --> 01:11:28.760
One of her books was published
by Yale, called The Fragile

01:11:28.760 --> 01:11:30.020
Middle Class.

01:11:30.020 --> 01:11:32.790
And it's about people who
go into bankruptcy.

01:11:32.790 --> 01:11:36.030
And she points out that in the
U.S., even back in the old

01:11:36.030 --> 01:11:38.920
days when the economy was
good, we had a million

01:11:38.920 --> 01:11:41.300
personal bankruptcies a year.

01:11:41.300 --> 01:11:43.910
This is because of borrowing.

01:11:43.910 --> 01:11:47.300
You don't know how many
bankruptcies there are,

01:11:47.300 --> 01:11:51.190
because people are ashamed when
they declare bankruptcy.

01:11:51.190 --> 01:11:53.180
And they try to cover
it up from as

01:11:53.180 --> 01:11:55.030
many people as possible.

01:11:55.030 --> 01:11:58.600
There are as many personal
bankruptcies in a normal year

01:11:58.600 --> 01:12:00.370
as there are divorces.

01:12:00.370 --> 01:12:01.680
But you don't hear about them.

01:12:01.680 --> 01:12:04.020
You hear about all kinds
of divorces.

01:12:04.020 --> 01:12:06.460
People are ashamed
of divorces, too.

01:12:06.460 --> 01:12:09.430
But they can't cover them up
because everybody knows.

01:12:09.430 --> 01:12:12.190
But they can pretty well cover
up a bankruptcy, and so they

01:12:12.190 --> 01:12:13.830
don't talk about it.

01:12:13.830 --> 01:12:17.370
So, what Elizabeth Warren is
saying, she thinks that the

01:12:17.370 --> 01:12:20.320
lending industry is victimizing
people.

01:12:20.320 --> 01:12:25.400
It's advertising for vacation
loans and the like, and then

01:12:25.400 --> 01:12:29.080
they don't tell people about the
bad things that will come.

01:12:29.080 --> 01:12:31.870
So, she wrote an article, and
this is interesting, it was in

01:12:31.870 --> 01:12:33.620
Harvard Magazine.

01:12:33.620 --> 01:12:37.360
And that's a magazine that I
suspect none of you read.

01:12:37.360 --> 01:12:40.510
Anyone read Harvard Magazine?

01:12:40.510 --> 01:12:43.760
It's the Harvard alumni
magazine.

01:12:43.760 --> 01:12:47.500
It goes out to all graduates
of Harvard.

01:12:47.500 --> 01:12:50.670
So, you don't read it, and you
probably will never read it.

01:12:50.670 --> 01:12:55.450
You will be a reader of the Yale
Alumni Magazine, which

01:12:55.450 --> 01:12:59.350
will start arriving in your
doorstep after you graduate.

01:12:59.350 --> 01:13:05.470
And it will also include your
obituary in the next century

01:13:05.470 --> 01:13:07.540
when that comes.

01:13:07.540 --> 01:13:10.780
But the Harvard alumni magazine
published this

01:13:10.780 --> 01:13:14.980
wonderful article about
Elizabeth, describing all of

01:13:14.980 --> 01:13:19.850
the abuses that happen in
lending in the United States.

01:13:19.850 --> 01:13:21.630
I don't know how I ended
up reading it.

01:13:21.630 --> 01:13:24.880
I think it was just such a
nicely written piece that it

01:13:24.880 --> 01:13:26.680
just became one of their
success stories.

01:13:26.680 --> 01:13:30.580
Most people don't read that
magazine, but I read it, and a

01:13:30.580 --> 01:13:31.760
lot of people have read it.

01:13:31.760 --> 01:13:35.940
And she was so successful in
convincing the public -- this

01:13:35.940 --> 01:13:39.690
is just two years -- or 2008,
three years ago --

01:13:39.690 --> 01:13:44.460
she was so successful that she
got a Consumer Financial

01:13:44.460 --> 01:13:49.140
Protection Bureau inserted
into the Dodd-Frank bill.

01:13:49.140 --> 01:13:54.430
And we now have a regulator, a
new regulator, that's supposed

01:13:54.430 --> 01:14:00.180
to stomp on these usurious
practices.

01:14:00.180 --> 01:14:02.750
It's kind of an inspirational
story, but the downside of it

01:14:02.750 --> 01:14:05.720
is, she got too carried away
criticizing the lending

01:14:05.720 --> 01:14:08.010
industry in that nice article.

01:14:08.010 --> 01:14:12.380
And it makes them sound worse
than they really are, and so

01:14:12.380 --> 01:14:17.260
Obama could not appoint her to
head the Consumer Financial

01:14:17.260 --> 01:14:20.600
Protection Bureau, because it
would be too politically

01:14:20.600 --> 01:14:21.320
controversial.

01:14:21.320 --> 01:14:26.240
So, she is now the person trying
to find someone to head

01:14:26.240 --> 01:14:28.190
her bureau.

01:14:28.190 --> 01:14:30.720
But I think that this is just
another step, and it's

01:14:30.720 --> 01:14:32.960
happening in Europe and
in other places.

01:14:32.960 --> 01:14:36.060
The financial crisis has
made us more aware of

01:14:36.060 --> 01:14:38.160
bad financial practices.

01:14:38.160 --> 01:14:40.640
And so, usury is again
on our minds.

01:14:40.640 --> 01:14:44.900
Usury is abusive lending that's
taken without concern

01:14:44.900 --> 01:14:47.220
for the person who's
borrowing.

01:14:47.220 --> 01:14:50.280
And I think what it means
to me is that --

01:14:50.280 --> 01:14:52.140
we'll come back to talk
about regulation in

01:14:52.140 --> 01:14:53.190
another lecture --

01:14:53.190 --> 01:14:56.520
but that the original Irving
Fisher story and von

01:14:56.520 --> 01:14:59.190
Boehm-Bawerk story about
interest was right.

01:14:59.190 --> 01:15:02.110
And even vacation loans,
especially

01:15:02.110 --> 01:15:04.190
honeymoon loans, are right.

01:15:04.190 --> 01:15:08.810
But we need government
regulation to prevent abuses.

01:15:08.810 --> 01:15:12.280
And we do still have abuses
in the lending process.

01:15:12.280 --> 01:15:15.710
So, I'll stop with that and
I'll see you on Monday.

